2500|$|Due to {{the wide}} {{proliferation}} of Buddhist texts available in Chinese and {{the large number of}} foreign monks who came to <b>teach</b> <b>Buddhism</b> in China, much like new branches growing from a main tree trunk, various specific focus traditions emerged. Among the most influential of these was the practice of Pure Land Buddhism established by Hui Yuan, which focused on Amitābha Buddha and his western pure land of Sukhāvatī. Other early traditions were the Tiantai, Huayan [...] and the Vinaya school. Such schools were based upon the primacy of the Lotus Sūtra, the Avataṃsaka Sūtra, and the Dharmaguptaka Vinaya, respectively, along with supplementary sūtras and commentaries. The Tiantai founder Zhiyi wrote several works that became important and widely read meditation manuals in China such as the [...] "Concise samatha-vipasyana", and the [...] "Great samatha-vipasyana." ...|$|E
